    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-21T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-21T04:00:00-05:00" n="555"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d555">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3700: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-21T17:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 21, 1922—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 25—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Group of Chinese banks have consented to buy Chinese treasury bonds amount
                    $14,000,000 repayable 20 equal monthly installments. Four millions of dollars of
                    bonds applied face value to extinguish Government’s obligations. Banks receive
                    discount $3,000,000 as interest on balance paid in advance, remainder will be
                    paid Government in cash after deducting 1.03 percent transfer <pb facs="0883"
                        n="763" xml:id="pg_763"/> charge. Security is salt surplus. Gamble<note
                        n="14" xml:id="d555fn14">Sir Reginald A. Gamble, associate chief inspector,
                        Chinese Government Salt Revenue Administration.</note> under Government’s
                    instructions has guaranteed to transfer to banks [$]700,000 monthly for service
                    bonds whenever surplus becomes available.</p>
                <p>Presidential orders 19th approve recommendations of Chinese Director General Salt
                    Administration for reform in service and negotiating above loan but stipulate
                    there shall be no further foreign or Chinese loans on this security.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
